description:
Should God’s people fear the final judgement? Why, instead, should we be grateful for it? Typology of Old Testament stories of deliverance shed light upon the deliverance of God’s people at the time of the final judgement described in Revelation.  

What can we learn from the stories of Abraham and his deceitful dealings with the pharaoh and Abimelech? What can we learn from the typologies embedded within the stories of the Exodus? How might a study of the stories of God’s dealings with Pharaoh, the Philistines, and Jezebel prepare us for how He will deal with those who tamper with His law? How do these stories reveal details about the antichrist and Satan’s strategies against God and His followers? What do they teach us about the final judgement?

What led up to the disastrous judgments that fell upon Jerusalem when the city was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD? When did Christians stop keeping Sabbath and begin keeping Sunday and why? What does the religion of the ancient pharaohs have in common with Roman Catholicism today? 

In this presentation, Professor Walter J. Veith looks at the typological elements of familiar Bible stories and fills in the details with information archaeology has revealed. What can history tell us about how prophecy will be fulfilled in the end? Why is the final judgement a thing not to be dreaded by God’s people? What can we learn from the Bible and history about the issues of the final conflict?

The Bible is a deep, inexhaustible well of comfort, guidance, and truth. Each of its stories contains elements of typology (the enactment of a greater truth), eschatology (final events), and soteriology (insights into the plan of salvation). This video examines these elements and presents a fresh look at old stories that have important lessons for us today.
